Recommendations:
We recommended and the management agreed that:
the City Mayor direct his City Treasurer to: a) immediately submit the paid DVs and its SDs relative to the afore-cited payment transactions; and b) comply with the timely submission of paid DVs together with its SDs to the City Accountant for proper accounting thereof;
the CTO exert effort in retrieve the staled checks from payees for the reissuance of the same; in case the check is lost, instruct the payee to execute an affidavit of loss to support the reissuance of check;
management reassess their internal control policy on releasing of checks and handling of vital financial documents, identify the weak points, and make the necessary revisions to prevent recurrence of the observation;
the City Accountant regularly furnish the City Treasurer the list of outstanding checks based on the monthly bank reconciliation for the latter’s appropriate steps to prevent said checks from becoming stale; and
the City Accountant strategize to facilitate timely preparation of monthly BRS as well as immediate identification of irregularities and effect necessary adjustment/taking up of reconciling items in the books of account.

Recommendations:
We recommended and the management agreed to:
revisit and enhance their internal control system, ensuring that proper safeguards in the disbursement of funds are in place;
craft guidelines that would aid in the assessment and evaluation prior to granting financial assistance;
provide clear and concrete basis on the computation of cash assistance to each qualified beneficiary; and
require the SDO to explain in writing why the deficiencies discovered during the validation of logbook entries were committed.

Recommendations:
We recommended and the Management agreed to:
henceforth, enhance their budget planning and preparation to optimize the utilization of government funds, particularly in the distribution of financial assistance;
maintain an updated database of Panabo City residents to ensure that the basis of budget preparation is accurate and complete; and to aid in the validation and verification process needed for financial aid programs;
address the adequacy of manpower during program implementation to expedite the delivery of social services to its constituents; and
strengthen its internal controls on special cash advances, to ensure that utilization and corresponding liquidation are in accord to prescribed guidelines.

We recommended and the management agreed that names of representatives from the NGOs, recycling industry, manufacturing/packaging industry and concerned government agency will be identified and designated to complete the SWM Board.
We further recommended and the management agreed that:
the CENRO strictly impose the use of protective equipment and paraphernalia such as gloves, mask and boots in handling solid wastes by the garbage collectors and re-emphasize to them its importance to their health;
the City Health Office capacitate the garbage collectors of the afore-mentioned barangays in handling solid wastes;
the ABC President assist in the monitoring of the untrained barangay garbage collectors and in identifying other deficiencies in the barangay solid waste management and present/coordinate the same to the City SWM Board; and
the SWM Board require the afore-cited barangays to indicate names and contact numbers in the garbage dumptrucks they used as garbage collection equipment.

We recommended the City Treasurer to:
coordinate with the City Assessor’s Office and devise a comprehensive strategy primarily focused on the collection of delinquent property taxes to substantially reduce the outstanding amount of delinquencies;
request sufficient funding for plantilla position and for other office needs to facilitate effective property tax collection, monitoring and assessment;
carefully consider deputizing the Barangay treasurers in remote barangays as collecting agents in accordance with Section 247 of RA no. 7160 to assist in the collection and monitoring of RPT accounts;
exert more effort in collecting the delinquent real property tax, impose all remedies available, and exercise taxing authority as mandated by Law; and
enforce collection of delinquent real property taxes by conducting tax campaigns and offer incentives for full payment of tax dues and prompt payment thereof.
We also recommended that the City Assessors Office (CASSO) to regularly update the classification of real properties to reflect proper assessment.

We recommended the following:

exert effort in identifying the nature of the previous years’ balances and make the necessary adjustments and reconciliations thereof to facilitate the immediate remittance of the same to the agencies concerned;

ensure full remittance of all taxes, contributions and loan payments withheld to avoid incurrence of unnecessary interests and penalties;

enhance internal controls by conducting regular reconciliation of amounts withheld and remitted to avoid over/under remittance; and

update the concerned agencies with any subsequent changes, as required by their respective policies, and do follow-ups if these changes were effected and implemented.

We recommended the following:

synchronize the GAD programs and activities listed in the GPB with the gender mainstreaming strategies in the AIP, to incorporate GAD mandates and gender issues that the City intends to address, and to maximize the utilization of funds for the benefit of intended beneficiaries;

conduct a thorough review in the crafting of GPB, in accordance with PCW DBM DILG NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, JMC 2016-01, as amended, and other applicable GAD rules and regulations;

strictly observe the timely submission of report at the time set by COA Circular No. 2014-01 dated March 18, 2014 to ensure the timely evaluation of GAD-related accomplishments; and

ensure the efficient delivery and implementation of GAD programs, projects and activities of implementing departments/offices to guarantee attainment the GAD objectives.

We recommended that the City Accountant:

Evaluate the non-moving balance aged more than a year and onward, whether or not dormant or unnecessary, requiring return to the National Treasury. However, if this is a case of unrecorded liquidation already utilized fund, adjustment is proper provided it is properly supported with evidence, whether documents and/or physical, in case it is a completed hard projects;

Draw the necessary adjusting journal entry to reconcile the subsidiary ledger of the donor or national agency against its statement of receipts and disbursements (SORD);

Correct and adjust all other balances to its appropriate account classification as discussed in this audit observation;

Implement all other previous years’ audit recommendation, such as that of the PDAF.

We recommended that the City Accountant:

Evaluate the non-moving balance aged more than a year and onward, whether or not dormant or unnecessary, requiring return to the National Treasury. However, if this is a case of unrecorded liquidation already utilized fund, adjustment is proper provided it is properly supported with evidence, whether documents and/or physical, in case it is a completed hard projects;

Draw the necessary adjusting journal entry to reconcile the subsidiary ledger of the donor or national agency against its statement of receipts and disbursements (SORD);

Correct and adjust all other balances to its appropriate account classification as discussed in this audit observation;

Implement all other previous years’ audit recommendation, such as that of the PDAF.

We recommended to the City Accountant the following:
To evaluate each balances especially those non-moving balances aged more than a year and onward, whether or not dormant or unnecessary requiring return to the National Treasury. However, if this is a case of unrecorded liquidation or fund already utilized, adjustment is proper provided it can  be proved by evidence, whether documents and/or physical, in case it is a completed hard project;
To draw the necessary adjusting journal entry to reconcile the subsidiary ledger of the donor or national agency against its statement of receipts and disbursements (SORD);
To correct and adjust all other balances to its appropriate account classification as discussed in this audit observation;
To implement all other previous years’ audit recommendation, such as that of the PDAF.

We recommended the following to the City Government:
That the City Engineer’s Office explain thoroughly the deficiencies and discrepancies noted in the review of documents and ocular inspection conducted by the COA;

The City should revisit the manner in which plans and specifications are prepared and require strict adherence to standards set to avoid bloated quantities and excessive costs in arriving at the ABC, POW and Detailed Estimates;

We also reminded the City of the possible disallowance of excessive and unnecessary items of work incorporated in the ABC, POW and Detailed Estimates
